The '''Catholic Association for International Peace''' was founded in 1927 by [[John A. Ryan]]. <ref>{{cite web |title=Archives |url=http://www.marquette.edu/library/collections/archives/Mss/CAIP/mss-CAIP.htm |accessdate=2008-08-01}}</ref> It based its opposition to war on the traditional [[just war]] doctrine.<ref>{{cite web |title=Harder than war |format=book review |url=http://rutgerspress.rutgers.edu/acatalog/__Harder_than_War_1899.html |accessdate=2008-08-01 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080720153012/http://rutgerspress.rutgers.edu/acatalog/__Harder_than_War_1899.html |archivedate=2008-07-20 |df= }}</ref>
It joined other religious organizations in urging a halt to the [[Operation Rolling Thunder|bombing of North and South Vietnam]].<ref>{{cite journal |last=Fiske |first=Edward B. |title=Religious Parley Urge Cease-fire. |issue=March 18 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1966/03/18/archives/religious-parley-urge-ceasefire-leaders-also-ask-johnson-to-halt.html?sq=%2522Catholic%2520Association%2520for%2520International%2520Peace%2522%2520Vietnam&scp=2&st=cse |accessdate=2008-08-01 | journal=The New York Times | date=1966-03-18}}</ref>
