{{Infobox scientist | name = Dorthe Dahl-Jensen | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1958|9|8|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Copenhagen]], [[Denmark]] | residence = Denmark | fields = {{plainlist | * [[Ice and Climate]] }} | workplaces = {{plainlist | * [[University of Copenhagen]] * [[Niels Bohr Institute]] }} | alma_mater = {{plainlist | * [[University of Copenhagen]] (M.Sc, Ph.D) }} | awards = {{plainlist | style = white-space: nowrap; | * [[Louis Agassiz Medal]] (2014) * EU [[Descartes Prize]] (2008) * [[Vega medal]] (2008) * Amalienborgprisen (2009) * Munch prisen (2009) }}
}}
'''Dorthe Dahl-Jensen''' (born 8 September 1958, [[Copenhagen|Copenhagen, Denmark]])<ref name="CV">{{cite web|last1=Dahl-Jensen|first1=Dorthe|title=Dorthe Dahl-Jensen|url=http://www.nbi.ku.dk/english/staff/?pure=en%2Fpersons%2Fdorthe-dahljensen(6d9a0017-8123-40da-8570-d3071cf77133)%2Fcv.html|publisher=University of Copenhagen}}</ref> is a Danish [[palaeoclimatology]] professor and researcher at the Centre for Ice and Climate at the [[Niels Bohr Institute]], [[University of Copenhagen]] in Denmark. Her primary field is the study of ice and climate, specifically the reconstruction of climate records from ice cores and [[borehole]] data; ice flow models to date [[ice core]]s; continuum mechanical properties of [[Anisotropy|anisotropic]] ice; ice in the [[Solar System|solar system]]; and the history and evolution of the [[Greenland ice sheet|Greenland Ice Sheet]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Niels Bohr Institute|url=http://www.nbi.ku.dk/english/staff/?pure=en/persons/45103|publisher=University of Copenhagen}}</ref>
==Education==
She has a M.Sc. In [[Geophysics]] (1984), and a Ph.D. in Geophysics (1988) from the University of Copenhagen.<ref name="CV" />
Dahl-Jensen led the North Greenland Eemian Ice Drilling (NEEM) project, which was a 14-nation research team which spent four years drilling and analysing the ice cores, the results of which were published in the journal ''Nature''.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=NEEM community members|title=Eemian interglacial reconstructed from a Greenland folded ice core|journal=Nature|date=24 January 2013|issue=7433|pages=489–494|url=http://www.nature.com/nature/journal/v493/n7433/full/nature11789.html|volume=493|doi=10.1038/nature11789|pmid=23344358|bibcode=2013Natur.493..489N}}</ref> The findings from this research revealed that "The NEEM core implies [contrary to most researchers' assumptions] that Greenland’s ice sheet lost at most one-quarter of its volume, and contributed no more than 2 metres of sea-level rise" which suggests that "Greenland is not as sensitive to [[Global warming|climate warming]] as we thought,"
==Current and up-coming projects==
In 2015, a collaborative group of researchers from the U.S., Germany, and Denmark will study Renland, Greenland area for deep ice core drilling.
Another project in early stages is a deep ice core drilling project, also located in Greenland which is expected to shed light on the northeast Greenland ice stream and its contributions to a rise in sea level. This could give details on what to expect for future sea level rise due to ice sheet mass loss in Greenland.
==Awards==
* EU [[Descartes Prize]] (as part of the [[European Project for Ice Coring in Antarctica]] (EPICA)) (2008) * [[Vega medal]] from the [[Swedish Society for Anthropology and Geography]] (2008) * Amalienborgprisen (2009) * Munch prisen (2009)<ref name="CV" /> * [[Louis Agassiz Medal]] from the [[European Geosciences Union]] (2014) - awarded "for her outstanding scientific contributions in polar glaciology and her leadership in international projects that have extended climate records from Greenland ice cores back into the last interglacial."<ref>{{Cite web|title = Dorthe Dahl-Jensen - Louis Agassiz Medal -|url = http://www.egu.eu/awards-medals/louis-agassiz/2014/dorthe-dahl-jensen/|website = European Geosciences Union (EGU)|accessdate = 2015-10-24}}</ref> * Member of the [[Royal Danish Academy of Sciences and Letters]]<ref>[http://www.royalacademy.dk/da/Members/201 member profile]; retrieved 2015-12-17</ref>
