'''Ragged Staff Guard''' is a fortification situated to the south of the [[British Overseas Territories|British Overseas Territory]] of [[Gibraltar]].

==Description==
The guard is located along the [[Line Wall Curtain]], and immediately beyond [[Southport Ditch]] immediately south of [[South Bastion, Gibraltar|South Bastion]], next to [[Ragged Staff Gates]] and the Navy boat sheds.<ref name="Finlayson2006">{{cite book|author=Fa & Finlayson|title=The Fortifications of Gibraltar 1068-1945|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BC5QBR0oB04C&pg=PA56|accessdate=9 May 2013|year=2006|publisher=Osprey Publishing|isbn=978-1-84603-016-1|page=56}}</ref> It was detached some hundreds of yards from all buildings, and supplied no posts within the city's gates. The guard house could be seen by approaching ships. In the 1840s it was said to be a full time job for the [[subaltern]] who was stationed here above a long flight of steps as he had to inspect every good that went through [[Ragged Staff Gates]].<ref name=pat>{{cite book|last=Patterson|first=John|title=Camp and quarters: impressions|year=1840|page=198|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=gHcEAAAAQAAJ&dq=%22ragged+staff+guard%22&source=gbs_navlinks_s}}</ref>  The guard house gained notoriety in the early 19th century as a [[yellow fever]] station.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Lancet|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_rQ1AQAAMAAJ&pg=PA420|accessdate=9 May 2013|year=1830|publisher=J. Onwhyn|page=420}}</ref>

==References==
:{{Source-attribution|J. Onwhyn's ''The Lancet'' (1830)}}
